Israeli Stocks: Ampal-American, Elron Electronic, Gazit-Globe

-- B y   S h o s h a n n a   S o l o m o n
-- 
2011-09-27T12:02:06Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-27/israeli-stocks-ampal-american-elron-electronic-gazit-globe.html
Israel ’s TA-25 Index increased for
a third day, gaining 1.2 percent to 1,075.46 at 2:28 p.m. in Tel
Aviv, paring the quarterly decline to 12 percent. The gauge has
retreated for three consecutive quarters, the longest streak
since March 2003.  The following stocks rose or fell today. Symbols are in
parentheses.  Ampal-American Israel (AMPL)  Corp slid 3.9 percent to
1.16 shekels, the lowest level since at least August 2006, when
Bloomberg started tracking the stock. An overnight explosion
damaged a  gas pipeline  from Egypt. Ampal said section of the
pipeline used by the company’s 12.5-percent owned East
Mediterranean Gas Co. wasn’t affected by the blast.  Elron Electronic Industries Ltd. (ELRN)   rose 2.5 percent
to 14.39 shekels, headed for the highest close since Sept. 1.
The technology company reached an agreement with a foreign bank
for a credit line of as much as $30 million.  Gazit-Globe Ltd. (GLOB)   climbed 3.9 percent to 38.05
shekels, the highest since Aug. 18. The real-estate investor’s
Atrium European Real Estate Ltd. unit acquired the Palac Flora
shopping center in Prague for 191 million euros ($260 million).  Separately, the company’s Equity One Inc. unit agreed to
sell 36 U.S. shopping centers to a Blackstone Group LP fund for
$473.1 million.  Kardan NV (KARD)   jumped for the second day, soaring 9
percent to 9.25 shekels. The investor in water infrastructure,
property and financial services yesterday said it will spend as
much as 15 million euros ($20 million) to repurchase shares.  Kazir Investments 1989 Ltd. (KZIN)   surged the most since
March 14, soaring 24 percent to 0.593 shekel. The investment
company plans to raise at least 75 million shekels ($20.2
million) through a sale of shares after which it will seek
investment opportunities in the oil and gas industry.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Shoshanna Solomon in  Tel Aviv  at 
